mission, but may be because it included sensitive information such as personal details.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>Their involvement in prominent medical and veterinary diseases makes herpesviruses one of the most important virus families. Herpes simplex virus?1 (HSV-1) ICP27 is a key protein required for expression of viral RNAs. A multifunctional regulatory protein with a counterpart in all herpesviruses of mammals and birds, ICP27 acts at transcriptional and post-transcriptional levels, to facilitate expression of viral mRNAs. It has an essential zinc binding region that is a target for the discovery of antivirals that act by ejecting zinc to inactivate its functions. ICP27 exerts its various activities through interactions with different cellular proteins involved in RNA processing and export, mRNA translation and protein phosphorylation. Such multifunctional proteins enable a co-ordinated and flexible system of gene regulation that deals with RNA transcripts from their synthesis to translation into proteins. Using the herpesvirus systems outlined, such co-ordinate regulation can be studied in detail, the information will be applicable to similarly acting cellular proteins that are less easy to study. 
Some proposals are a continuation of existing work, but mostly they arise from new insights. We have shown an involvement of ICP27 in cytoplasmic RNA localisation and regulation of translation perhaps via poly (A) binding protein. The co-localisation of HSV-1 transcripts to enable co-ordinate translation in the cytoplasm will be investigated. Microarrays will identify the viral and cellular RNAs that co-immunoprecipitate and bind proteins within the ICP27-containing complex. Contributions of the multifunctional ICP27 partner protein heterogeneous nuclear ribonucleoprotein K (hnRNP K) to viral replication will be examined. 
Functional characterisation will be carried out of HSV-1 RNA sequences shown to enhance gene expression via both ICP27 and an cellular factor(s). This analysis will be extended to the clinically important varicella-zoster virus (VZV) where most genes have HSV-1 counterparts although the viral genomes have very different G+C contents to inform on similarities and differences in terms of protein-RNA recognition and RNA function. between ICP27 and ORF4 proteins. ICP27 and its Kaposi?s sarcoma herpesvirus ORF57 protein counterpart may access transport pathways other than the mRNA nuclear export route previously identified. We will determine if they recognise export factors in addition to REF and TAP and examine interactions with cellular nucleoporins. Finally, NMR protein structural studies, with viral RNA ligands, will provide information on how ICP27 may function and help the design and optimisation of antiviral compounds.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-06-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>1999-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>1949802</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs><gtr:collaborationOutput><gtr:collaboratingOrganisation>Wellcome Trust</gtr:collaboratingOrganisation><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:department>Wellcome Trust Centre for Cell Biology</gtr:department><gtr:description>HSV-1 and nuclear periphery</gtr:description><gtr:id>17996C01-0A75-4037-904C-80743365A433</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Malik P, Tabarraei A, Kehlenbach RH, Korfali N, Iwasawa R, Graham SV, Schirmer EC. &amp;quot;Herpes simplex virus ICP27 protein directly interacts with the nuclear pore complex through Nup62, inhibiting host nucleocytoplasmic transport pat